00:01.540 --> 00:09.220
Okay? Okay. You got the tape going? The tape is rolling. Okay. What I've done,
Mr. Knight, is simply to, as I said, you've done so much. You've been so

00:09.220 --> 00:17.160
involved in the field that it was hard to get a handle on how to approach this.
But what I've done is sort of divide up into different areas, and I'll ask you

00:17.160 --> 00:26.280
some brief questions on each one. And the first one would involve your entry
into science fiction. You came through the fan structure, and I wondered if you

00:26.280 --> 00:32.480
could explain how you were introduced to that. I sort of thought that might come
up, and I was rooting about it a little yesterday.

00:35.500 --> 00:45.340
Actually, I was thinking, what if you asked me to where I would contribute my
gigantic success? I would have to say mostly luck. I can trace my career back

00:45.340 --> 00:55.600
through a series of just astounding coincidences, really unlikely things, all
the way back to Hugo Gernsback. And I can demonstrate that at each of these

00:55.600 --> 01:03.580
points, If something rather unlikely had not happened, I wouldn't be doing what
I'm doing. For instance, if Hugo Gernsback had not come to this country from

01:03.580 --> 01:15.280
Luxembourg when he was 14 and started a magazine called Amazing Stories in 1926,
you'll see as I go on that none of the other things could have happened. So here

01:15.280 --> 01:25.480
I am, a 13-year-old kid in Hood River, Oregon, reading science fiction
magazines, really turned on by them. and through the back pages of one of these

01:25.480 --> 01:36.100
magazines super science stories then edited by Frederick Bull I found out about
the fanzines and rode away for a few and this way got into correspondence with

01:36.100 --> 01:50.640
the Futurians including then Bull and Wollheim and Cyril Kornbluth and a bunch of
others Robert Dudley Lowndes I was trying to write some stories and I sent a

01:50.640 --> 02:03.980
couple to Lowndes, who was then acting as a sort of half-assed literary agent.
And all these things added up together until Donald A. Wollheim got an offer from

02:03.980 --> 02:12.260
a publisher to edit a new science fiction magazine. He had no budget, whatever,
for stories. And he knew about me from Lowndes. Lowndes wrote to me saying, will

02:12.260 --> 02:22.820
you donate this story to the first issue of Superstirring Science Story? And of
course I said yes. I would have paid for the privilege. And as a consequence of

02:22.820 --> 02:33.460
that, the Futurians invited me to come and be a Futurian, live in one of their
communal dwellings in New York when I was 18. Terribly unlikely thing, just a

02:33.460 --> 02:43.480
series of them, even as far as we've gone. And I lived there a couple of years
doing little illustrations from magazines and trying to write. Not deceiving

02:43.480 --> 02:57.900
very much. And then in 1943, Again, it was Fred Pohl, got me a job at popular
publications where he was working. I needed an assistant editor, and he knew I

02:57.900 --> 03:06.080
would work cheap. So he got me an interview where I got the job. Spent about a
year there, and I'm perfectly convinced now, looking back, that it was that

03:06.080 --> 03:14.000
training at popular publications that enabled me to write fiction
professionally. It was a training that you couldn't get in any school. How did

03:14.000 --> 03:23.440
you get it now? But it just kind of soaked in because I was reading the slush
pile, the unsolicited manuscripts, and it became perfectly obvious after a while

03:23.440 --> 03:32.740
what the difference was between the stuff we were rejecting and the stuff we
were printing. So when I quit that job, I started writing and went on from

03:32.740 --> 03:43.400
there. I did another stint later at Popular, 1949. And I also worked for a while
at the Scott Merritt's Literary Agency, which was a reading fee agency, where we

03:43.400 --> 03:51.640
would get these awful manuscripts and have to criticize them. I think that
helped me a good deal, too. If I could recommend the writing, or the training

03:51.640 --> 03:59.980
for young writers, I would certainly say it's too bad that those pulp magazines
don't exist anymore. You can possibly get an editorial job or anything of that

03:59.980 --> 04:13.020
kind. Even a terrible job in the reading fee literary agency. Okay. Okay, we
talked to Frederick Pohl some time ago and he told us a little about the

04:13.020 --> 04:21.520
Futurians and of course you've written a book on that too Could you be a little
more specific, sort of briefly what your relationship with the Futurians was

04:21.520 --> 04:34.220
what exactly they did? Well, the Futurians were a very informal organization of
science fiction bands who were trying to become professional and in some cases

04:34.220 --> 04:43.820
had a little bit of impact of success here and there, published stories. I told
you that Wollheim was editing a magazine. Before him, Pohl had become an editor.

04:44.640 --> 04:50.420
After him, Lowndes also became an editor. They were writing and publishing a
little bit, not much.

04:53.180 --> 05:05.540
To save money, because they were all very poor, they lived in a communal
apartment. At that time in New York, in the late 30s and early 40s, There were

05:05.540 --> 05:16.580
lots of apartments among them that were very cheap. I forget now. I think the
rental might have been about 30 bucks for a four-bedroom railroad flat. If you

05:16.580 --> 05:24.360
had four people living there, it was quite cheap. And we divided up the
household duties around with the cooking. And I did the fish washing, which I

05:24.360 --> 05:36.960
hated. We were dirtboard. We really didn't have any money at all. We rolled our
own cigarettes, and we bought the cheapest wine we could find, which was

05:36.960 --> 05:38.620
something like 85 cents a gallon.

05:41.800 --> 05:51.460
Our major entertainment was walking down from 102nd Street, or 103rd, it was,
down to Times Square, and looking at the bright lights and having a cup of

05:51.460 --> 05:53.820
coffee in the cafeteria and then walking home.

05:56.780 --> 06:05.760
I read once where your actually your first professional sale was a cartoon is
that right I suppose that's right I hadn't thought about that it was a cartoon

06:05.760 --> 06:13.120
that I sent to Amazing Stories which was before I went to New York before I told
a story I must have been 17

06:16.000 --> 06:30.280
I sent some other ones and I didn't like them okay your if I'm correct here
your earliest work in the fanzines was of a critical nature and I wondered if

06:30.280 --> 06:38.940
that's true why you started out with did you just have a critical bent or did
you not want to write creatively at first I was trying to write fiction at that

06:38.940 --> 06:48.140
time and not succeeding I couldn't finish stories I didn't have any idea of how
you got to the end of the story but I was extremely critical and starting like

06:48.140 --> 06:51.700
any other right 17 or 18 year old fan

06:54.620 --> 07:04.980
The first stuff I did for fanzines was not critical in the usual sense. I mean,
it wasn't book-reviewed or that kind of thing, but it was parody mostly. The

07:04.980 --> 07:17.940
things that I thought were really outstandingly dumb in the magazine, funny
enough to parody, and I did a lot of that. But when I say a lot, I lie, because

07:17.940 --> 07:31.560
I only published two issues of my fanzines and did very little for other
magazines. It was much later, sorry, about 1945, I think. I did a long critical

07:31.560 --> 07:40.920
essay about Van Gogh for one of Larry Shaw's amateur magazines. That was really
the first critical work in the usual chemical I did.

07:44.960 --> 07:53.020
From what I've read of your, say, your collected essays and so forth, the things
that you've done in terms of criticism, I would say that probably your major

07:53.020 --> 08:04.080
concern overall has been to deal with the question of science fiction as a
higher, to raise its literary standards perhaps, to make it something more than

08:04.080 --> 08:15.040
just a kind of a second class kind of literature. And I wondered if you thought
that science fiction could ever compete with mainstream and characterization,

08:15.540 --> 08:23.560
human relations, and so forth, or is it too limited to do that? Well, that was
my position, And I didn't see any reason why science fiction shouldn't be as

08:23.560 --> 08:28.160
good as any other kind of fiction can be. I don't think now that it ever has
been.

08:31.300 --> 08:41.380
And I still have, and I have a few doubts now about whether it can be. But at
that time, as you say, my effort was to try to raise the standards, improve the

08:41.380 --> 08:44.420
breed, mainly by shooting cripples.

08:48.700 --> 09:00.600
you maybe have some doubts now whether science fiction could ever produce
somebody like say a Dostoevsky then yeah of course mainstream hasn't produced

09:00.600 --> 09:12.440
another Dostoevsky either so these comparisons are really not much help but in
the 50s there was a really strong invigorating movement to upgrade science

09:12.440 --> 09:23.040
fiction in certain ways by lifting it out of the Pope formulas. H.L. Gould was
responsible for part of that and Tony Boucher for another part, and it really

09:23.040 --> 09:34.080
seemed to me that we were on a plateau which could quite well be succeeded by
another plateau and so on, upward. And I think that was what I was pushing for.

09:35.040 --> 09:46.760
I haven't seen it happen. We have some very good work being done, very literary
work, But it doesn't seem to me that the field as a whole has advanced as much

09:46.760 --> 09:49.820
as I expected it would beyond the 1950s.

09:52.120 --> 10:03.960
Would you see any big changes in the field since you began? Oh, muchos. I
started reading in 1933 and picked up all the back issues I could find in second

10:03.960 --> 10:10.560
-hand bookstores in Portland. and the situation in the 30s

10:14.020 --> 10:25.220
was a little fragmented. By that time, Gernsback had lost his magazines, and he
didn't have Gernsback in SF anymore. His idea was to teach science through

10:25.220 --> 10:34.780
science fiction. He didn't always do it, but that was his ideal. And then you
had his successor at Amazing Stories, T. O'Conor Sloane, who was then in his 80s.

10:35.700 --> 10:45.580
I never met him, but he was described as a marvelous, white-bearded old
gentleman who considered science fiction a sort of a hobby. What he liked was

10:45.580 --> 10:57.120
archaeology. And he really did not have any of the technocratic fervor that
Gernsback has. In fact, he said in print more than once that he didn't believe

10:57.120 --> 11:01.820
that space travel would ever happen. And then you had

11:04.580 --> 11:17.220
astounding stories which in the early 30s was strictly a rather low grade
adventure magazine their contribution to the field was to import the stereotypes

11:17.220 --> 11:30.200
of adventure fiction which worked very well and we still see that thread running
through science fiction right up to the present time and then in the late 30s

11:30.200 --> 11:43.740
37, 38 John Campbell took over astounding and more or less transformed it he
raised the level in a certain direction he wanted scientific accuracy or at

11:43.740 --> 11:59.560
least a semblance of it lack of scientific ignorance he wanted plausible stories
about the future not the usual triad of a brave hero and his jodhors and amen,

12:00.100 --> 12:12.180
and the fainting heroine and the mad scientist. So in that sense, and also
because he got a, um, stable of very good writers in the early 40s, that raised

12:12.180 --> 12:24.500
the level considerably, markedly. And then as I say, Gold and Boucher and others
came along in the 50s, and there was another quantum leap. And it seemed to me

12:24.500 --> 12:34.360
that that was the natural course of the dance. What we wanted was another
quantum leap. so on until there would be no distinguishable difference in terms

12:34.360 --> 12:44.160
of quality between science fiction and mainstream. And as I say, I don't think
that happens. Some of those quantum leaps in the past that you've mentioned have

12:44.160 --> 12:52.860
been due, I think, to, as you said, to some of the more influential editors. Do
we have editors today who still have that kind of influence? Well, I think we

12:52.860 --> 13:01.880
have certainly influential editors, but I don't think they're trying to do that.
I think they're trying to produce what they conceive the reading public wants

13:01.880 --> 13:12.560
and they're very successful at it. George Sithers, for example, is a very sharp
editor. And Stanley Schmidt, I think, is doing an excellent job with analog. And

13:12.560 --> 13:22.220
of course Ed Furman has been working along with fantasy and science fiction for
many years. Publishing a lot of really neat stuff. Fantasy and science fiction

13:22.220 --> 13:33.160
has always had a more literary cast. and the other magazines, partly because
it's about half and half fantasy and science fiction, as the name would suggest.

13:34.000 --> 13:39.560
And for some reason, the literary quality of fantasy writing has tended to be
higher than that in science fiction.

13:42.940 --> 13:53.720
Okay, listen, when you began your Orbit anthologies in 1966, what kind of hopes
did you have for them? What was your idea behind them? Well, in the first place,

13:53.720 --> 14:01.560
I just thought there was a marketing strategy there that hadn't been explored.
Please forgive my costs.

14:05.100 --> 14:18.420
It seemed to me that with hardcover publication, if you could get book club and
paperback, you'd have a basis on which you could pay very good rates and get a

14:18.420 --> 14:29.600
broad audience. and that because it was hardcover, originally you wouldn't have
to worry about some of the pulp cliches on the juvenile reader. And that didn't

14:29.600 --> 14:43.040
work either. Orbit never did achieve the sales that I hoped for or the
publishers hoped for. It got a few book club sales but not many. It wasn't every

14:43.040 --> 14:53.500
issue, it should have been. And the paperback never did sell very well. So after
they went to harbor with the series, they couldn't get paperback at all, and

14:53.500 --> 15:01.080
that was what made them cancel it after a while. They hung on quite a long time.
They were very decent about it. But eventually they saw that this wasn't going

15:01.080 --> 15:01.440
to happen.

15:04.580 --> 15:15.340
Well, was that the first anthology of original science fiction that was
published? No, it was not. Fred Poole had done a series called Star. Let me

15:15.340 --> 15:26.500
think. It must have been in the late 50s. I forget. and before him there had
been a couple of one shot original anthologies I've forgotten who the editors

15:26.500 --> 15:38.040
were, let me think I used to I think the first one actually goes back quite a
way it was something rather inconspicuous and nobody paid much attention but

15:38.040 --> 15:48.620
Fred was the first series of anthologies of original science fiction stories In
terms of the I guess the literary level of the orbit series, so you must be

15:48.620 --> 15:55.580
proud of that through some of those years, that I think the majority of the
Nebula Award stories came from orbit, didn't they? For a couple of years, it was

15:55.580 --> 16:02.220
scoring heavily in the nebulas, yeah. But I don't really know whether that has
anything to do with the quality of the stories, or just because I was

16:02.220 --> 16:04.880
conspicuous at the time, I was the president of SFWA.

16:08.560 --> 16:15.880
Yeah, that leads me onto the next area I want to talk about. You had a large
part in the founding of that. Could you explain your part in that and why you

16:15.880 --> 16:27.460
were interested in starting it? Well, about ten years earlier, it must have
been, there was an effort to form a guild of science fiction writers, and I went

16:27.460 --> 16:37.820
to one or two of their meetings, and it was pitiful because they used the
parliamentary procedure and they had 50 people all arguing, and they finally

16:37.820 --> 16:49.660
hammered out a set of bylaws and elected officers, and then nothing happened.
The officers all went home and died. And I realized at that time that there was

16:49.660 --> 16:57.680
a very easy way to do it. You didn't have to have the big meetings, and you
didn't have to have all that apparatus. One person could do it. But I didn't

16:57.680 --> 17:11.780
think I was conspicuous enough at that time. I didn't think anybody knew who I
was. Later on, I was becoming more visible, and I realized that I probably could

17:11.780 --> 17:25.820
do it. the precipitating event was by receiving in the same week three requests
for anthology reprints for flat fees, which I thought was unfair to the author.

17:26.340 --> 17:37.840
So I wrote a flyer, the one-page thing, advising authors not to sign agreements
for flat fee anthology reprints, and saying, if you'd like more information of

17:37.840 --> 17:47.360
this kind, send in your three bucks and become a charter member of SFWA. So I
got a flock of responses. When I had about 78, I declared them the charter

17:47.360 --> 17:58.960
members and wrote a set of bylaws and sent that around, and we were more or less
in business. Okay, and what did you serve? One or two years as president? I did

17:58.960 --> 18:08.800
two terms. Okay, and you'd have to look back. Wouldn't you have to judge it
today as a successful organization? I think so. I think it's done more for

18:08.800 --> 18:17.740
members than any other writer's organization that I know of. We got about 9,000
bucks in back royalties for Tolkien and lots of things for

18:21.320 --> 18:36.100
isn't that awful, her name just popped out of my head. Andrew Norton. And we've
settled a lot of grievances. The latest one was a really terrible new contract

18:36.100 --> 18:49.220
which Davis Publications began to use. Just an awful contract. Gobbling up both.
every right conceivably attached to a story, and we made such a stench that they

18:49.220 --> 18:50.260
withdrew it.

18:54.560 --> 19:02.080
About a year ago, we talked to Norman Spinrad, I guess, who's the current
president, and he said he was interested in working on internationalizing or

19:02.080 --> 19:09.300
hooking up with some of the European organizations. Do you think that's a good
idea? There's a lot of feeling among the members that we ought to be more

19:09.300 --> 19:18.380
international than we are. I always resisted that because it didn't seem to me
that we could work effectively for writers living abroad and not publishing in

19:18.380 --> 19:23.880
this country. I guess it's harmless. I don't see that it could do us any damage.

19:27.080 --> 19:35.460
Okay, let me move on to one more area before I get down to just a few questions
on your own work. I guess you realize I'll probably have to ask something about

19:35.460 --> 19:46.940
the Milford Science Fiction Writers Conference. Could you also give me a brief
statement on the genesis of that? Well, this was in the mid-50s, and for some

19:46.940 --> 19:53.680
reason, Judy Merrill and I got talking about the idea of having a writer's
conference in Milford, Pennsylvania, which is a very small town in the Poconos.

19:55.960 --> 20:06.360
It was sort of the way you might talk about building a boat in the basement, and
nothing was done about this until Judy and I went to the World Con in Detroit, I

20:06.360 --> 20:18.000
think it was, and discovered that he was much more better than we realized.
Well, that energized us, and we thought that possibly if we invited people to

20:18.000 --> 20:30.720
the military, they could actually come. And we sent out the invitation. We got
Jim Wish to join the masthead, lend it more respectability, and this was the

20:30.720 --> 20:43.680
year in which the following year of New York, so it was easier for people to get
out there directly afterwards. Then we got 40 people. Just amazing. It was quite

20:43.680 --> 20:58.180
intense. We had evening discussions that went on for several hours with people
raising parts of hands to do the next to speak. Quite exciting. So we decided to

20:58.180 --> 21:12.900
do it annually. After the first one, we didn't have a World Con near us to
provide all that many people. and the attendance dropped to, I don't know, 15 or

21:12.900 --> 21:25.080
so. When it gradually came up again, we began to get a bunch of regulars who
came every year and then there'd be a few more and so on. So in the later years,

21:25.080 --> 21:35.200
we got up to about 25 or 30, which was really as much as we could handle in the
workshops, which by then had become a regular feature of Milford, where

21:35.200 --> 21:45.360
everybody would submit a manuscript or two. And then every morning we'd all sit
around having read these manuscripts and discuss them in turn around the

21:45.360 --> 21:45.620
surface.

21:48.720 --> 21:56.940
This is probably an obvious question, but I want to ask it anyhow to see your
response. Do you think writers are, what kind of benefit, what kind of benefit

21:56.940 --> 22:07.500
would writers get from that? Have they been benefited? Well, this is a question
that Katie and I ask ourselves every year because we teach at Clarion, which is

22:07.500 --> 22:19.380
an outgrowth of Milford. And you can certainly point to lists of distinguished
ex-Milfordites and Marianites. It is a distinguished list. But whether that

22:19.380 --> 22:31.500
proves anything or not is another question. You have to have a control group
which we have never had. I can testify that if you could help me in a specific

22:31.500 --> 22:38.140
way. the workshop helps. People point out what it was in your story that you
absolutely haven't seen, sometimes crucially.

22:40.640 --> 22:51.000
And, again, just from my own experience, it seems to me that learning to
criticize other people's stories technically enables you eventually to criticize

22:51.000 --> 22:56.580
your own, which is a difficult thing at all. It becomes a little bit easier to
see the flaws in your own.

23:00.080 --> 23:10.600
okay you're not associated with the Milford conference anymore then no, we had
to stop doing it five or six years ago don't hold me to the number because I'm

23:10.600 --> 23:19.960
very weak on dates it turned out that year that we had signed up for so many
things in the summer that were going to have to drop something and it couldn't

23:19.960 --> 23:29.660
be clarion we were committed to that so we had to stop doing Milford and it
wasn't really a a painful loss to us by that time because our old gang

23:29.660 --> 23:30.280
dispersed.

23:32.740 --> 23:43.120
We had moved away from Milford first to Florida and then to Oregon. And it just
wasn't the same thing anymore. It was turning into more of a sort of mini

23:43.120 --> 23:52.320
clarion where you had the chiefs and the Indians. Katie and I were the chiefs
and the rest were Indians which had not been the case at all at Milford. That

23:52.320 --> 24:06.840
was by design and practice. a group of peers. So that Milford, as it has turned
out, has become sort of a duplication for us of what we were doing at Clarion.

24:08.760 --> 24:19.820
Ed Bryan has done it a couple of times, about every year, in Denver or
thereabouts. And it is still going on. But the difference between the two, like

24:19.820 --> 24:24.680
you said, the Clarion would be more for actual beginners, where you would be the
teacher rather than peers.

