the paperback editor but I published portions of it in magazines and one of them
had the title that I preferred A for anything

25:20.020 --> 25:32.220
I hate the title of the people maker Okay in that book The A for Anything I'm
sure you've gotten questions on this in fact I know you have but the totally

25:32.220 --> 25:42.800
unexpected ending that comes up at least I as a reader expected the protagonist
I forget his name right now to become sort of a good guy to overcome his

25:42.800 --> 25:54.740
training and to let the old slave live and to marry the woman and so forth why
did you choose to have him revert to his stratified, slave-oriented society?

25:56.800 --> 26:07.720
Well, what you're talking about, the ending that you expected is the cliche
ending, romantic and sentimental. I wanted to do a realistic ending. I thought

26:07.720 --> 26:16.520
that the happy ending to that, you know, a conventional, quote, happy ending to
that novel would have been false. And this was one of the things that's

26:16.520 --> 26:23.980
interesting in writing the novel in the first place. You know, anything I've
done, except for the slapstick. I was trying to do science fiction

26:23.980 --> 26:36.200
realistically. I thought that was part of the new wave. It wasn't called that
then, but the wave of realism that came in the 50s. And I was awfully enthired,

26:36.380 --> 26:39.180
still I am, of the romantic cliches of science fiction.

26:42.600 --> 26:52.880
Okay, the device that you put into that novel, The Gizmo, The Transform Society,
it's kind of ironic that a device like that which can give people whatever they

26:52.880 --> 27:02.800
want would lead to a slave master society do you think that's the way it would
work or would you be being deliberately pessimistic? well, I thought it was

27:02.800 --> 27:16.540
logical I was counter-punching in that novel against some other treatments of
the same device the same gadgets that had been published before which I thought

27:16.540 --> 27:27.720
were cop-outs. For instance, George Oak Smith wrote one in which the matter-to
-date duplicator was invented, and of course chaos ensued, and he rescued the

27:27.720 --> 27:38.380
world by inventing a kind of currency that couldn't be duplicated. And that was
one too many rabbits out of the hat, I thought. So, again, I just wanted to do

27:38.380 --> 27:53.600
it realistically. It seemed to me that if I had made a good case that, in fact,
slavery would be the No, I admit that it was an imaginative projection. I don't

27:53.600 --> 28:04.820
necessarily defend the idea that that's what would happen in practice. And
